        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "A–5 It sufices to prove that for any relatively prime positive integers r, s, there exists an integer n with an = r and an+1 = s. We prove this by induction on r + s, the case r + s = 2 following from the fact that a0 = a1 = 1. Given r and s not both 1 with gcd(r, s) = 1, we must have r ≠ s. If r > s, then by the induction hypothesis we have an = r − s and an+1 = s for some n,; then a2n+2 = r and a2n+3 = s. If r < s, then we have an = r and an+1 = s − r for some n; then a2n+1 = r and a2n+2 = s.",
